    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, can you help me understand the difference between a \"confidentiality period\" and a \"survival clause\" in a standard contract? I'm trying to make sure I don't miss anything important.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A **confidentiality period** defines the specific timeframe during which your obligations to keep information secret are enforceable, effectively setting an expiration date for that duty. In contrast, a **survival clause** specifies which other contract terms remain binding for a set time *after* the entire agreement has officially terminated. While one limits the duration of a specific duty, the other ensures critical post-termination obligations, such as payment or dispute resolution, continue to hold weight regardless of the agreement's end date.",
      "source": "target",
